                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d629">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_MHF1">Matthews</persName> files, lot 53 D 413:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Commander in Chief, United Nations Command (<persName
                            corresp="#p_CGMW1" type="from">Clark</persName>) to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Joint Chiefs of Staff</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>operational immediate</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Seoul</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-06-23T09:20:00+09:00"
                            >June 23, 1953—9:20 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Unnumbered, DTG 230020Z. Re DTG 221100Z<note n="1" xml:id="d629fn1">Dated June
                        22, <ref target="#pg_1231">p. 1231</ref>.</note> after considering further
                    the proposal suggested in para 5<hi rend="italic">d</hi> (4), reference message,
                    an alternate which would probably avoid difficult negotiations and possibly
                    complicated political factors would be to move the Chinese non-repatriates to
                    the <gloss target="#t_DZ1">D/Z</gloss> and turn them over the <gloss
                        target="#t_NNRC1">NNRC</gloss> in the same manner as the Korean
                    non-repatriates. This would be a difficult logistical task, but am sure it could
                    be overcome.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
